Create Notification Elements in HTML:

You can create empty notification elements at the top of your HTML page. For example:

html

<div id="successNotification" class="notification">Operation was successful</div>
<div id="errorNotification" class="notification">Operation failed</div>
Define CSS for Notifications:

You can use CSS to style and control the appearance of the notification elements. In this example, I'll keep it simple with minimal styling. You can adjust the styles as needed.

css

.notification {
  display: none;
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 100%;
  background: #333;
  color: #fff;
  padding: 10px;
  text-align: center;
}
JavaScript to Show and Hide Notifications:

Here's how you can use JavaScript to show and hide notifications for a few seconds:

javascript
// Function to show a notification for a few seconds
function showNotification(notificationElement, message, duration) {
  notificationElement.textContent = message;
  notificationElement.style.display = 'block';
  setTimeout(() => {
    notificationElement.style.display = 'none';
  }, duration);
}

// Example usage:
// To show a successful operation notification for 3 seconds:
showNotification(document.getElementById('successNotification'), 'Operation was successful', 3000);

// To show an error notification for 3 seconds:
showNotification(document.getElementById('errorNotification'), 'Operation failed', 3000);
Display Notifications After Operations:

After performing an operation, such as adding a new blog or handling a login attempt, you can call the showNotification function to display the appropriate notification.

For example, when a new blog is added successfully:

javascript

// After successfully adding a blog
showNotification(document.getElementById('successNotification'), 'Operation was successful', 3000);
And when a login attempt fails:

javascript
